WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.200
Hello, my name is Alan Feder and I am a Principal Data Scientist at Invesco.

00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:18.020
My talk today is about Categorical Embeddings and the Embed Package in R.

00:00:18.020 --> 00:00:23.440
If you are trying to create a predictive model, you'd really like to use all of the variables

00:00:23.440 --> 00:00:31.980
in your dataset as that's what's likely to create the most accurate and successful predictions.

00:00:31.980 --> 00:00:37.919
But you may soon run into a problem because many of the functions within R that are used

00:00:37.919 --> 00:00:44.840
to create these models require that all of the input data are continuous numbers.

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:50.160
Now this makes sense because many of the computations that go on in the background work on linear

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:55.080
algebra and matrices, which inherently can only have numbers in them, but that might

00:00:55.080 --> 00:01:00.480
be a problem for you because some of your data might be categorical variables and you

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:02.900
don't want to have to drop them.

00:01:02.900 --> 00:01:10.400
You might try to replace each category with a number, 1, 2, 3, which might work if your

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:16.800
data is ordinal, but if your data doesn't have any inherent order to it, this might

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:18.040
not work.

00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:24.919
If one of your categories is color, how are you going to choose numbers for black, brown,

00:01:24.919 --> 00:01:27.320
yellow, or green?

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:33.760
You might try to create dummy variables, but this actually can cause big data problems

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:35.839
really quick.

00:01:35.839 --> 00:01:44.400
Dummy variables will create a new variable for each level of your data and, for example,

00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:51.440
if one of your categories is United States ZIP Code, you're about to add 42,000 new variables

00:01:51.440 --> 00:01:55.680
to your data and that's probably not what you want.

00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:59.199
That leads me to categorical embeddings.

00:01:59.199 --> 00:02:05.000
If you're familiar with word embeddings, such as Word2Vec, this is actually a very similar

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:12.800
idea, except instead of an embedding for each word in language, you're embedding each category

00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:16.440
in your data.

00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:21.320
What happens is that every category is replaced by a vector of numbers.

00:02:21.320 --> 00:02:26.639
The vector can be length 4, it can be length 50, it really depends on the situation, but

00:02:26.639 --> 00:02:33.839
these numbers will replace your categorical variable for any future modeling.

00:02:33.839 --> 00:02:40.479
Now, categorical variables are most commonly fit by neural networks, which is why within

00:02:40.479 --> 00:02:47.440
R, many of the most common ways of creating them are using the Keras and TensorFlow packages

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:49.399
or the new Torch package.

00:02:49.399 --> 00:02:55.639
However, I find the simplest way to do it is with the embed package, which is one of

00:02:55.639 --> 00:03:02.360
the add-on packages in the tidy models suite of packages.

00:03:02.360 --> 00:03:07.720
For example, let's say you had a data set of sales transactions and you wanted to predict

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:12.479
which transactions are fraudulent and which ones are not.

00:03:12.479 --> 00:03:17.279
Having product in there, you can imagine how that would help the predictive ability of

00:03:17.279 --> 00:03:24.759
the model, but with over 4,500 unique products, that's going to cause problems with creating

00:03:24.759 --> 00:03:27.199
your model.

00:03:27.199 --> 00:03:34.360
But with the embed package, all you have to do is add one function, step embed, onto a

00:03:34.479 --> 00:03:38.039
tidy model's recipe to create this embedding.

00:03:38.039 --> 00:03:45.240
Once you've prepped this recipe, the embeddings are there for use.

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:52.399
And you can see here how each product is now represented by an embedding of four numbers.

00:03:52.399 --> 00:03:58.240
And these four numbers are going to replace the old product category within the data going

00:03:58.240 --> 00:03:59.240
forward.

00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:02.679
You can now use this for any downstream model.

00:04:02.679 --> 00:04:05.679
It doesn't even have to be a neural network.

00:04:05.679 --> 00:04:11.119
You could also use this, if you wanted, just to explore your data further and learn more

00:04:11.119 --> 00:04:12.880
about the products.

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:17.519
Maybe you could use cosine similarity to figure out which products are most similar to each

00:04:17.519 --> 00:04:18.519
other.

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:23.799
Now, there's obviously a ton more that I could talk about with categorical embeddings.

00:04:23.799 --> 00:04:27.079
It's a topic that I find really exciting.

00:04:27.079 --> 00:04:34.160
I hope you learn and discover more about categorical embeddings as you use them within your modeling.

00:04:34.160 --> 00:04:36.399
Thank you very much for coming, and good luck.

